Summary
This January 2y report from BOC Group draws on insights from nearly 300 organisations across multiple industries to examine the current state and future trajectory of BPM adoption and maturity. The report reveals that while BPM adoption is widespread, maturity levels remain low: only approximately 15% of organisations have reached an advanced maturity level. The report identifies key 2026 trends including the shift toward evidence-based process improvement through process mining (with 13% of organisations planning to implement it), the embedding of compliance into process design rather than treating it as a reactive activity, and the increasing expectation that BPM must deliver measurable return on investment rather than just process documentation.
Justification
I chose this artefact because it contextualises the Process Analysis topic within a broader organisational reality that I had not previously considered: that even though BPM frameworks and methodologies are well-established, most organisations still struggle to implement them at a mature level. This connects directly to the Week 2 lecture content on the BPM Digital Value Framework, which emphasises that a value-driven transformation approach is vital for organisations seeking to move from compliance-driven process management to innovation-driven improvement (ABPMP International, 2019, p. 53). The finding that only 11% of organisations currently use diagnostic analytics such as process mining — despite its recognised value — was surprising and highlighted a significant gap between theory and practice. It reinforced the Week 3 lecture's argument that organisations should conduct process analysis continuously, not just in response to isolated events (ABPMP International, 2019, p. 132). This artefact has shaped how I now think about the role of a future BPM professional: not just as a technician who maps processes, but as a change agent who advocates for evidence-based, continuous improvement culture.


